The idea and execution are fantastic. The gameplay is fun and challe√¨nging, without being frustrating at the same time. Having active spells to aid you while you juggle resources makes combat fun and engaging, although sometimes when your heroes use their skills at the wrong time or in the wrong manner that is frustrating. The game has a solid concept and stunning graphics, but some other aspects really brought the experience down. And most of the downside falls on UI and control.  The buttons are so tiny, the words are so tiny. It's impossible to read the label of heroes to summon, it's impossible to read what's the upgrade cost. This game would be OK if played on PC with NOX, but on a small screen, it's not enjoyable. Want to swipe up that card to upgrade that low HP hero? Whoops, missed the card, the whole screen just flew away and your hero died. Want to circle heal your heroes when you just gathered them together? Whoops, missed the heal because I clicked on the damage skill instead. This is a mobile strategy game, not how accurate you can push small buttons game.  A few other smaller complaints: game speed not adjustable/no check points. On longer levels and you lose to boss or you missed 3 stars, it really adds to the frustration that you just have to start over again. You can't skip or speed up. At the end of the day what matters is if the game is enjoyable, and for me, although the art and graphics are stunning, the poor UI and gameplay makes the experience frustrating.

It's an interesting spin on the classic TD genre, I'll give you that. It's uniqueness is about all the game has going for it.  As many others mention, the small controls on a phone are tricky but I didn't find them to be impossibility so.  Bosses are, well, boring. They all require the same strategy to defeat and are more of a chore than a pleasure to fight. Hurt them a little bit, dodge red spots on the ground, repeat until dead.  Some units I found to be essential, others felt useless.  To end on a positive note, the art style is lovely (even if many levels are dark) and there's a decent variety of enemies.

I've rated it 4 stars for a few reasons, most notably because the controls can be a bit fiddly. The ability to zoom in a bit more would probably help with this. My second complaint is that I can't go back to earlier levels and use my new units or upgrade levels. I'd definitely recommend it for the price!

content: Great game

EDIT: I actually appreciate your reply, and increased my rating by one star. To elaborate, my disappointment is because, with original art concepts, this could have been a truly unique thing that would have been yours. I don't think it's far-fetched when I say this game rips-off, or at least heavily leans on, the art direction and menu/upgrade systems of Kingdom Rush. The game's premise is great, and with original artistic direction it would have been phenomenal. Every aesthetic aspect to me leans heavily on Kingdom Rush, from the animation and menus to level and unit designs. This game has certainly piqued my interest in you as developers and like I said, I'm impressed with the game itself, so I'll be following you guys in the future. I just would have really loved to have seen you really run with original ideas instead of relying on derivative art concepts for what could have been a  TRULY unique twist on what's becoming a stagnant game genre.
replyContent: Update: Thanks for elaborating on your reply as well! We understand where you're coming from, but would also like to point out that with the same device limitations, genre, and what we had in mind - we decided on what could best showcase our ideas. Hopefully we will meet someday to have a chat over this! :)

Kurechii has a knack for creating fun-to-play computer games. Their form is almost immediately recognizable - simple, yet stylish designs, rounded characters, new or altered takes on classic games, and customizable gameplay despite a linear story. Each and every game they have released sports these characteristics, and Tiny Guardians is no exception.   Allow me to summarize. Tiny Guardians is a game where you, the player, follows the path of Lunalie, the Summoner, as she journeys through a world searching for her master, the Sorceress, who has mysteriously disappeared. Along the way, you must protect Lunalie from a wide variety of rather numerous hostiles, choosing from a selection of fighters in order to achieve this goal. These fighters (your "guardians") are upgradeable, allowing you to choose a strategy which fits your playing style.   Overall, Tiny Guardians is a well-made game. The only drawback I've seen is the limited number of levels. There are enough to keep you hooked, but when you finish the game, that's it. I suggest adding another chapter to solve this.

This is a great spin on the tower defense genre. The art is pleasing and the game is fairly tight. The basic premise is you have a small group of semi customizable heroes who traverse each map on rails. You can choose the types of unit and their placement in the group. Customization is not super in depth, but it is there in the form of linear skill trees. So far it is not pay to win, just for skins and early unlocks. Everything else can be unlocked through game play.
Got plenty more to play so can't fully rate. Would recommend to Kingdom rush fans
